#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:1
msgid "Design"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:3
msgid "Give each unit a single responsibility (`single-responsibility`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:5
msgid ""
"Each module, type, or function should have one, and only one, reason to "
"change. If you cannot describe what a unit does without the words \"and,\" "
"\"or,\" or \"but,\" it has too many responsibilities."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:11
msgid "This applies at every scale:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:13
msgid ""
"**Functions** should do one thing, do it well, and do it only. If you can "
"extract another function from it with a name that is not merely a "
"restatement of its implementation, the original function is doing more than "
"one thing. Do not mix levels of abstraction: a syscall handler should read "
"like a specification, while byte-level manipulation belongs in a helper."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:20
msgid ""
"**Files** should hold one concept. When a file grows long or contains "
"multiple distinct concepts, split it — each major data structure, subsystem "
"entry point, or significant abstraction deserves its own file."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:26
msgid "// Good — each function operates at one level of abstraction\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:32
msgid "// Bad — mixes high-level logic with low-level details\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:40
msgid "// ... 30 more lines of byte parsing ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:44
msgid ""
"See also: _Clean Code_, Chapter 3 \"Functions\"; PR [\\#639](https://github."
"com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/639#discussion_r1524629393)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:48
msgid "Don't repeat yourself (`dry`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:50
msgid ""
"Every piece of knowledge should have a single, unambiguous representation. "
"Duplication harms readability and maintainability. When the same pattern "
"appears three or more times, eliminate the duplication (e.g., by adding a "
"helper function)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:56
msgid "Hide details behind interfaces (`information-hiding`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:58
msgid ""
"Hide details behind well-defined interfaces. A module's public surface "
"should contain only what its consumers need. Internal data structures, "
"helper types, and bookkeeping fields should remain private, and "
"implementation details should not leak through public APIs (including their "
"documentation)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:66
msgid ""
"See also: [`narrow-visibility`](rust-specific/crates-and-modules.md#narrow-"
"visibility) for Rust-specific visibility rules; PR [\\#2951](https://github."
"com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2951#discussion_r2786925410)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:71
msgid "Be open for extension, closed for modification (`open-closed`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:73
msgid ""
"Stable modules and APIs should be open to extension but closed to breaking "
"modification. Prefer adding new behavior through existing interfaces "
"(traits, enums, and pluggable components) instead of repeatedly editing "
"established call paths. Do not introduce extension points preemptively; add "
"them when there is a concrete extension need."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:83
msgid "Follow the principle of least surprise (`least-surprise`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:85
msgid ""
"Functions, types, and APIs should behave as their names and signatures "
"suggest. When an obvious behavior is not implemented, readers lose trust in "
"the codebase and must fall back on reading implementation details. Prefer "
"names and API shapes that users already know from Rust and Linux; do not "
"invent new terms for well-known operations."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:95
msgid "// Good — follows common Rust naming conventions\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:98
msgid "// Bad — unfamiliar synonyms for common operations\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:104
msgid "Aim for loose coupling and strong cohesion (`coupling-cohesion`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:106
msgid ""
"Connections between modules should be small, visible, and flexible. Within a "
"module, every part should contribute to a single, well-defined purpose."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:111
msgid "Be consistent (`consistency`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:113
msgid ""
"Do similar things the same way throughout the codebase. Consistency reduces "
"surprise and cognitive load even when neither approach is objectively "
"superior. When a convention already exists, follow it; do not introduce a "
"competing convention without compelling justification."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:120
msgid "Take a Rust-native approach (`rust-native`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:122
msgid ""
"Asterinas is inspired by Linux but is not a C port. The language shapes how "
"we think about problems: where C code relies on conventions and manual "
"discipline (return-code checking, paired init/cleanup, header-file "
"contracts), Rust offers compiler-enforced, zero-cost abstractions (the `?` "
"operator, RAII, trait bounds)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/design.md:129
msgid ""
"Learn from Linux's design, not its idioms. The result should read like "
"idiomatic Rust, not like C written in Rust syntax."
msgstr ""
